Allocating memory dynamically in C++ can be done using several methods, including using the new and delete keywords, using smart pointers, and using the std::make_unique and std::make_shared functions.

The new keyword is used to allocate memory for a new object, and the delete keyword is used to free the memory that was allocated by the new keyword. For example:

```
int* ptr = new int;
*ptr = 42;
delete ptr;
```

Smart pointers are a type of pointer that automatically deallocate memory when it is no longer needed. This can help prevent memory leaks and other memory-related errors. For example:

```
std::unique_ptr<int> ptr(new int);
*ptr = 42;
```

The std::make_unique and std::make_shared functions can be used to create unique or shared pointers, respectively.
